/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:15:The phrase "one baseline burden that a reformulation would have to beat" is also unstable. Burdens in this area come in different currencies: derivative count, locality, pressure recoverability, integrability, sign structure, solution-class admissibility, and scaling compatibility. The chain says these will be frozen, but it does not say how incompatible currencies will be compared. Without that, "beat the burden" can mean almost anything.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:43:This is where the chain tries to become honest, and it is also where it is weakest. "Write one explicit localization or contradiction line" understates the complexity of endpoint insertion. LEI/CKN arguments do not usually hinge on a single line; they depend on a tightly coupled stack of local energy, pressure decomposition, scaling, covering, and compactness. A candidate that helps one displayed line can still fail because it wrecks admissibility or cannot be threaded through the rest of the proof skeleton.
